Title: Non-Neutral and Quasi-Neutral Toroidal Equilibria with Sheared Rotation  
Author: O. A. Hurricane 
Note: Typeset using REVT  
Address: Los Angeles 405 Hilgard Ave., Los Angeles, California, 90095-1547  
Affiliation: Department of Physics, University of California at  E X  
Abstract: Starting from the fundamental ion and electron fluid equations, a "master" equilibrium equation set is constructed for axisymmetric toroidal plasmas. These equations retain the effects of different ion and electron densities and temperatures as well as sheared rotation and electric forces. The master equation is then examined in various limits including the non-neutral plasma limit. In the pure electron plasma case, the resulting equilibrium equation includes the effects of toroidal rotation, poloidal magnetic field, and electron pressure extending the equation of Daugherty and Levy [Phys. Fluids, 10, 155, 1967]. An ordering is constructed in such a way as to make the effects of the Reynolds stress, pressure, magnetic stress, and electric field stress all comparable emphasizing the natural transition from the non-neutral case to the quasi-neutral one. For charge separation effects to be important, one discovers that the magnetic field must be virtually force-free and that the plasma fi must be very small or the flow must be relativistic. The final quasi-neutral plasma equilibrium equation is a modification of the usual Grad-Shafranov equation. Finally, this equation is solved numerically for a few choices of parameters and the resulting equilibria are presented. PACS 52.25.W,52.30, 52.55 
